 probably not include this. The telephone&nbsp;participation can be done as a routine matter whether or &nbsp;not it&#39;s in the bylaws, but if it&#39;s here, it runs the risk of being construed as a required option to be provided, and opens up a risk that someone who wanted&nbsp;to participate in this way but ran into technical issues challenges the validity of the vote.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref8" id="cmnt8">[h]</a><span class="c15 c12">Very similar writing in ISTTs bylaws but only for the Board or committees and no mention of voting:</span></p><p class="c9 c21"><span class="c15 c12"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Section 18. Meetings by Virtual Conference Applications or by Conference Telephone. Any one or more members of the Board of Directors or any committee thereof may participate in a meeting of such Board or committee by means of a conference telephone, virtual conference application or similar communications equipment allowing all persons participating in the meeting to participate equitably. Participation by such means shall constitute presence in person at a meeting.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref9" id="cmnt9">[i]</a><span class="c15 c12">ESIP considers in person and remote participation as equivalent, including for the purposes of voting; but they also allow electronic voting via fora such as email.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref10" id="cmnt10">[j]</a><span class="c15 c12">favoring ranked choice voting</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref11" id="cmnt11">[k]</a><span class="c15 c12">Staggered terms may be wise</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref12" id="cmnt12">[l]</a><span class="c15 c12">replace with: at least 18 years of age.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref13" id="cmnt13">[m]</a><span class="c15 c12">A simple majority&nbsp;of those present opens us up to a vocal minority&nbsp;electing a board to push a specific agenda. If a quorum&nbsp;of a simple majority is not present then the election of the board should not be ratified until the votes of a majority&nbsp;of members&nbsp;is obtained electronically.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref14" id="cmnt14">[n]</a><span class="c15 c12">Agree, enable electronic voting!</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref15" id="cmnt15">[o]</a><span class="c15 c12">emailed?</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref16" id="cmnt16">[p]</a><span class="c15 c12">Should the title be executive director?&nbsp; I think that is the function being performed here.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref17" id="cmnt17">[q]</a><span class="c15 c12">An ED normally is staff, and answers to the Board, and the President of the Board and an ED are normally very distinct. My reading of the draft is essentially that for now RIIS will not have an ED.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c12 c15">1 total reaction</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Rami Saydjari reacted with &#128077; at 2024-07-28 04:42 AM</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref18" id="cmnt18">[r]</a><span class="c15 c12">That seems like an awful lot of responsibility&nbsp;for an uncompensated Board member. I&#39;m skeptical that this is tenable. I think a decision needs to be made as to whether there&#39;s a compensated ED or an uncompensated President of the Board, but I don&#39;t think you can have both in the same person and have it go well.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref19" id="cmnt19">[s]</a><span class="c15 c12">It is likely that we won&#39;t have funding for even a part-time ED; for a good long time.&nbsp; In that case, this becomes overseeing the treasurer and their collection of funds/accounting for volunteer time; overseeing the volunteers to make sure things like the IT stays up.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref20" id="cmnt20">[t]</a><span class="c15 c12">I know that this is what the language&nbsp;is saying. My point was that in the absence of a compensated ED, it is unsustainable to pin this responsibility on an uncompensated officer. The responsibility should perhaps instead rest with&nbsp;the Board as a whole. But I know I would not ever sign up for an uncompensated Board position with this much executive responsibility, and I&#39;d argue the pool of people who would and could is going to be very narrow and un-diverse. I don&#39;t think this point has been addressed at all yet.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref21" id="cmnt21">[u]</a><span class="c15 c12">forbidden?&nbsp; We need firm procedures around these capabilities....</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref22" id="cmnt22">[v]</a><span class="c15 c12">Actually, shouldn&#39;t these be publicly available along with the by-laws and procedures?</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref23" id="cmnt23">[w]</a><span class="c15 c12">A caution would be deliberations of a highly sensitive&nbsp;nature regarding for example the dismissal of a member. If we are to make these minutes public then personally identifiable information may have to be redacted to minimize legal consequences.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref24" id="cmnt24">[x]</a><span class="c15 c12">I would not include anything in the bylaws that in effect requires, or that can be construed to require, any paper records. (Some paper records may be required by law, IRS, funding agencies etc, but there is no need to repeat or duplicate those here.) Speaking from experience, paper records create a huge nightmare in secure storage and handover. It is best avoided as much as allowed.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref25" id="cmnt25">[y]</a><span class="c15 c12">&#128077;</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref26" id="cmnt26">[z]</a><span class="c15 c12">ISTT bylaws in reference to the Secretary&#39;s responsibilities for record keeping:</span></p><p class="c9 c21"><span class="c15 c12"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">&quot;keeping the minutes of all meetings of the</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Board of Directors and the General Assembly; registering the minutes in the corresponding minutes book, and transmitting them to the webmaster for archiving on the ISTT website; maintaining all legally required books and membership records, and safeguarding the documentation of the Society.&quot;</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref27" id="cmnt27">[aa]</a><span class="c15 c12">Actually I think it is necessary to see a treasurers report at every board meeting.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">1 total reaction</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Rami Saydjari reacted with &#128077; at 2024-07-28 04:49 AM</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref28" id="cmnt28">[ab]</a><span class="c15 c12">I think the members should have a way to oust / replace the board also.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref29" id="cmnt29">[ac]</a><span class="c15 c12">Yes! But the membership&nbsp;doing so should require a large amount of consensus.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref30" id="cmnt30">[ad]</a><span class="c15 c12">I assume time spent as a Director would count towards the Director&#39;s volunteer hours in service of Ronin?</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref31" id="cmnt31">[ae]</a><span class="c15 c12">Grounds for Removal:</span></p><p class="c9 c21"><span class="c15 c12"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">A director may be removed from the board for any of the following reasons:</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Failure to attend a specified number of board meetings (e.g., three consecutive meetings or a set percentage of meetings within a year).</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Engaging in conduct detrimental to the interests of the Corporation.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Violation of the Corporation&#39;s bylaws or policies.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Any other reason deemed sufficient by the board, provided it is not arbitrary or capricious.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Initiation of Removal Process:</span></p><p class="c9 c21"><span class="c15 c12"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">The removal process can be initiated by a majority vote of the board of directors or by a petition signed by at least [specified percentage, e.g., 10%] of the voting members of the Corporation.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Notice of Removal:</span></p><p class="c9 c21"><span class="c15 c12"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">The director subject to removal shall be given written notice of the proposed removal at least 15 days prior to the board meeting where the removal will be considered. The notice shall state the reasons for the proposed removal and the date, time, and place of the meeting.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Opportunity to be Heard:</span></p><p class="c9 c21"><span class="c15 c12"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">The director subject to removal shall have the opportunity to respond to the reasons for removal, either in writing or in person, at the board meeting where the removal will be considered. The director shall be allowed to present evidence and call witnesses if desired.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Vote on Removal:</span></p><p class="c9 c21"><span class="c15 c12"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">The removal of a director shall require a two-thirds (2/3) majority vote of the remaining directors present at a meeting where a quorum is present. Alternatively, if the removal was initiated by a petition of members, a two-thirds (2/3) majority vote of the voting members present at a properly called meeting shall be required.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Effective Date of Removal:</span></p><p class="c9 c21"><span class="c15 c12"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">If the vote for removal is successful, the removal shall be effective immediately unless otherwise specified in the resolution.</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Filling of Vacancy:</span></p><p class="c9 c21"><span class="c15 c12"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Any vacancy on the board of directors created by the removal of a director shall be filled in accordance with the provisions of Section 9 of this Article.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref32" id="cmnt32">[af]</a><span class="c15 c12">Do you truly mean _officers_, and not _members_ of the Board? I would make the bar higher, such as 3/4. Board decision in which 1/3 of the board didn&#39;t participate just seem questionable by default. It also allows scheduling meetings such that a third can&#39;t participate.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref33" id="cmnt33">[ag]</a><span class="c15 c12">ISTT bylaws, pretty strict:</span></p><p class="c9 c21"><span class="c15 c12"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">A quorum shall consist of not less than a majority of the entire Board.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref34" id="cmnt34">[ah]</a><span class="c15 c12">Really?</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref35" id="cmnt35">[ai]</a><span class="c15 c12">Right. It seems weird that it wouldn&#39;t be whole board that does this.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref36" id="cmnt36">[aj]</a><span class="c15 c12">ISTT bylaws:</span></p><p class="c9 c21"><span class="c15 c12"></span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Section 15. Committees of the Board. The Board of Directors may, by resolution or resolutions adopted by a</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">majority of the entire Board, constitute committees that will address specific concerns of the General Assembly,</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">each consisting of at least one Director and other members from the General Assembly as needed.</span></p></div><div class="c2"><p class="c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref37" id="cmnt37">[ak]</a><span class="c15 c12">ISTT does not allow compensation for being an officer:</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Section 8. Compensation. No Officers shall receive any compensation for duties related to his/her status as an</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Officer, either by way of salary, fees for attendance at meetings, or otherwise, or shall be reimbursed for his or</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">her expenses, except pursuant to authorization of the General Assembly. This section shall not preclude any</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">Officer from serving the Society in any other capacity or from receiving compensation for such services and</span></p><p class="c9"><span class="c15 c12">reimbursement for his related expenses.</span></p></div></body></html>